Problem
I had a scenario where a single data model needed to support multiple valid configurations, but:
Each configuration had different required fields
Some fields were mutually exclusive
Using a single constructor would lead to:
Too many optional parameters
Invalid object states
Excessive null checks
==============================================================

Naive Approach (What Goes Wrong)
class Task {
  final String? userId;
  final String? referenceId;
  final String type;

  Task({
    required this.type,
    this.userId,
    this.referenceId,
  });
}
Problems:
Allows invalid combinations:
type = A but userId = null
type = B but both fields provided
Validation shifts to runtime
Harder to maintain and debug
==============================================================

Improved Approach – Named Constructors
class Task {
  final String? userId;
  final String? referenceId;
  final TaskType type;

  Task._({
    required this.type,
    this.userId,
    this.referenceId,
  });

  // Type A → requires userId
  Task.typeA({required String userId})
      : this._(
          type: TaskType.typeA,
          userId: userId,
        );

  // Type B → requires referenceId
  Task.typeB({required String referenceId})
      : this._(
          type: TaskType.typeB,
          referenceId: referenceId,
        );

  // Type C → requires both null
  Task.typeC()
      : this._(
          type: TaskType.typeC,
        );
}

enum TaskType { typeA, typeB, typeC }
==============================================================

Benefits
✅ Enforces valid states at compile time
✅ Prevents invalid field combinations
✅ Improves readability of object creation
✅ Reduces null-check clutter
✅ Keeps initialization logic centralized
==============================================================

Key Insight
Named constructors are useful when a class has multiple valid initialization paths with different constraints.
==============================================================

When to Use
Use named constructors when:
Object has fixed variants
Each variant has different required inputs
You want to prevent invalid states early


